# Git workflow — PR first

## Default (all code and docs)

Never push commits directly to `main` or `origin/main`.

1. Create a feature branch from `main` (e.g. `feat/...`, `fix/...`).
2. Commit only the relevant changes.
3. Push the **branch** to `origin` (`git push -u origin HEAD`).
4. Open a pull request with `gh pr create` (title + summary + test plan).
5. Wait for review/merge; do not force-push to `main`.

Do not use `git push origin main` for application code, infra, docs, or CI.

## Exception — shared Cursor config (`.cursor/**`)

Changes under `.cursor/` (rules, skills, project settings) are **team-wide agent config**.

For `.cursor/**` only:

1. Commit on `main` (or merge quickly after a tiny PR if the repo requires it).
2. Push directly to `origin/main` so every developer gets the same rules on pull.

When a task touches both `.cursor/` and other files, split into two commits/branches: push `.cursor/` to `main`; put everything else in a PR.

## PR checklist

- `git status` / `git diff` before commit
- PR describes **why**, not only what
- Include a short test plan when behavior changes
